<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100800730139298></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100800730139298><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=2&mid=100800730139298>RE: newbie to class</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=2&mid=100800730139298#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73658><span id=Sage>DavivMcD</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>193 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Dec 10th 1:01 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>It could definitely be worth developing archery, but keep in mind that in the long run rogues are better suited to throwing. The big advantage of throwing over archery are the deadly strikes. They are pretty much like backstabs; you have to be behind the mob and it does like 5 times the regular damage. Also, the level 60 skill assassinate (does 32,000 dmg to level 48 or lower mobs) is possible off of a deadly strike when throwing just like it's possible off of a backstab when stabbing.<br><br>On the other hand, archery has a longer range and a better array of weapons to choose from.<br><br>Personally, I'd stick with the throwing. A rogue doesn't make the best puller; you want the mob to be attacking someone besides the rogue right from the beginning of the battle.<br>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD 26th Dwarf Rogue<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
